.TH _PRINTF 3 "March 2026"
              "Holberton School"
              "Library Functions Manual"
                  .SH NAME
                      _printf \-
    produce output according to a format

        .SH SYNOPSIS
        .nf
#include "main.h"

    int _printf(const char *format, ...);
.fi

.SH DESCRIPTION
The _printf() function writes output to the standard output stream
according to a format string. The format string is composed of zero or
more characters and conversion specifiers.

Characters are written as-is, except that conversion specifiers
introduced by '%' are replaced with values from the variable argument list.

Supported conversion specifiers:
.TP
.B %c
Prints a single character.
.TP
.B %s
Prints a string of characters. If the argument is NULL, the string "(null)" is printed.
.TP
.B %d, %i
Prints a signed decimal integer.
.TP
.B %%
Prints a literal '%' character.
.TP
Unknown specifiers
If an unknown specifier is encountered, _printf prints the '%' character
followed by the specifier character literally.

.SH RETURN VALUE
The _printf() function returns the total number of characters printed
(excluding the terminating null byte used to end output to strings).
If an incomplete format specifier is encountered (for example, a single
'%' at the end of the format string), the function returns -1.

.SH EXAMPLES
.nf
_printf("Hello, %s!\n", "world");
Prints : Hello, world !

         _printf("Number: %d\n", 42);
Prints : Number : 42

         _printf("Percent sign: %%\n");
Prints : Percent sign : %
                            .fi

